Reduce number of calls to findPantsRoot 1. findPantsRoot was called indirectly by JarMappings::librariesFile.
This was happening on each VFS event, so could be expensive
2. librariesFile needs BSP roots path. Previously it was extracted from expensive
`importsFor` method.
3. Now, the `importsFor` method is simplified, so it just takes BSP root from `getBasePath`. This means
we don't support cases when two `.bloop` projects are imported into a single IJ project. Anyways, the
support for this was never used or tested.

Synchronous refresh The `idea dump-shared-index` command does not work when refresh is asynchronous. Indexing starts
when refresh is not finished yet, so no modules are loaded to the project yet. Therefore we need
a way to control it.

Target spec view fixes (#562) * Support non-canonical Pants addresses

Before, the only supported formats were:
  PATH:
  PATH::
  PATH:TARGET

Now we support also address without colon:
  a/b/c
which is equivalent to a/b/c:c

Relative paths were set in case if user has extended project with the "+" button in "Pants"
window

As its return type is Optional, one might not expect it throws

Seems like cache size in Travis is somehow limited

https://travis-ci.community/t/builds-timeout-during-or-shortly-after-creating-directory-home-travis-cache-sccache/5001/2

Merge events happening during python sdk setup (#559) As per advice from jetbrains, I wrapped calls that mutate project model into mergeRootsChangesDuring. I also removed the unnecessary commit that doubled number of calls.
On project with 1700 modules, the freeze time is down from 2 minutes to below 20 seconds, but freeze is still there.
The update needs to happen in write action and it affects a lot of modules and handlers for roots change will be invoked, so I don't think we can avoid any freezing in current intellij. I added a notification that informs the user for how many modules the update will be invoked and that ide may freeze.

Extend open project tests (#556) * Add support for querying python facets with their python sdk
* Improve custom pants building with timeout and error message reporting
* Bump ide-probe version to latest
* Cleanup accidentally commited binary files
* Rename `targetSpecs` to `pants.import.targets`

Do not call get project.getBasePath (#558) This method may return incorrect value. The case is that the user may
create project literally *anywhere* and tnen import BSP project to
it. `getBasePath` will return path to the directory where the project
was created.

Apart from that, since this commit the `sources-jar` dir is also
recognized as project internal dependency (updated
`isProjectInternalDependency` method)

Update for scala plugin 2020.2.717 (#555) This PR is to test if everything still works with latest scala plugin. Also updates package, as it changed for one of extension points in scala plugin we are using.
We can merge it as is, or wait till the breaking api change is in stable release and revert changes in sh scripts.
Bump thrift plugin to 1.2 in probe tests (#553)

Bump ideprobe to use ij 2020.2 (#545) This PR bumps ideprobe tests to use Intellij 2020.2.

Also it has a rewrite/reorganization of tests to avoid unnecessary starting intellij so many times for basic open project checks, as well as removes duplicate tests and adds pants/bsp variants for everything that makes sense.

Finally, it has reorganized CI running mechanisms (splitting into separate jobs because tests are quite slow on CI (locally 30 min to complete all) and using a published docker image to shorten time to setup everything.

New "Project Files by Target Specs" view (#551) Add a new tab to the "Project" panel, that may be used to browse
filesystem, but limits visible directories only to the ones that
directly match rules defined in Target Specs, so it does not show
folders containing dependencies unless they are not outside the target
spec directories.

Enable python facet setup (#547) I uncommented the code to bring back the feature that was disabled. I also changed it to be synchronous as if it is async, the map with interpreters it is supposed to fill will be empty, and the code later can't use it. Also moved setting up sdk paths out of write action.

The changes in test teardown are related to https://youtrack.jetbrains.com/issue/IDEA-246356 bug that I found.

* Manually close all projects

EditorEvent listeners are unsubscribed from the bus when the project
is closed. Previously it was done by

that checked if no listeners leaked. For some reason, since 2020.2,
the subscription list is not cleared correcly during tearDown, so this

Enable ideprobe for pants plugin CI (#540) This PR enables a way to run ide-probe tests for intellij pants plugin.

I added new element to travis matrix (ideprobe) which runs test.sh script inside docker. 

The docker image just setups packages needed to run probe and pants (python, xvfb etc.) and coursier and accepts an agreement needed to run intellij. 

The `run_docker` script builds pants plugin and passes it down to docker container.

test.sh script is used inside docker to run tests. It enables virtual display to run tests with full gui. Then it installs ideprobe artifacts to ivy local repo (eventually we should just use a published version and proper resolvers). 

Tests are run using junit standalone launcher (run via coursier). Coursier is also used to build the classpath required to run ide-probe (the framework and tests). The tests for pants are inside artifact 
`com.virtuslab.ideprobe:pants-tests_2.13:0.1:test` and the jar for this artifact is passed as `scan-classpath` flag for junit to run only pants related tests. 

There is one more thing here. At the beginning of runtime classpath we put one more jar with `pants.conf` file. In ide-probe it contains common config for pants tests: intellij and plugin versions. Thanks to this we control have control over versions here and also we can use the pants plugin from current PR. In similar way it is possible to override any other probe config externally.

Further things to do with this integration:
- Note that I disabled PantsIssue42 test, it is quite heavy as it reproduces an issue and ensures it's not there anymore, but to do this is sets up 2 extra versions of pants. Running this causes exceed of the max 90min time for a travis job. In general, tests will need to be split (probably with set of more granular include/exclude patterns to fit in. 
- Screenshots - ide probe takes screenshots during ui tests, we can make them available to look at for failing tests. We will just need to see how to do this in travis and implement it.

Generate source jars on demand for internal dependencies (#529) The resulting workflow is:
* User navigates to class file without sources.
* Intellij opens editor with decompiled file stub and a yellow bar on top of that editor
* The bar shows: "Decompile to Java", "Choose Sources..." and a newly added option "Import Sources * from Pants".
* After clicking on new option, if the jar the .class file is in is located under bloop-jars we do the following
* extract target name from it by naming convention
* ask pants for source files in this target (filemap)
* resolve source root based on package or heuristics for given source
* pack all sources into jar (<original-name>-sources.jar) that is created right next to the jar with classes
* new jar is attached as sources for all libraries that contain this .class file

Add automatic fastpass update notification (#526) After loading first project there is a thread that starts watching the system fastpass version located at /opt/twitter_mde/bin/fastpass. If version is different (read from bloop.settings.json) it creates a notification with "Update" link. When clicked it kills bloop, runs fastpass refresh command (with the system version) and triggers project refresh.

Save incremental import depth setting (#504) This change was reverted, because we thought it broke CI. But after
reversion the CI is still red with the same errors.

ORIGINAL COMMIT HASH
1f72954

ORIGINAL MESSAGE

Before this commit, IntelliJ plugin was asking for incremental import
depth each time, even when doing refresh. The depth value was not
saved anywhere.

Now, the incremental import depth parameter is saved alongside other
settings, and may be configured in the same place as others.

Action to convert pants project to bsp (#516) Adds an action to Pants menu in Pants projects that starts a background task. This task runs fastpass to generate project with the same name as the original project has and the same targets as were selected for the project.

Idea 201.5259.13 support (#498) The major obstacle was that scala plugin for 2020 is being compiled with jdk 11, hence we can no longer run the pants-plugin test suite with the jdk 8.
Our solution is to:
A) set the 'java11' platform for test targets(misc, jvm-ibtegration and so on)
B) force pants-plugin to use JDK 8 when running pants within test cases but use JDK 11 to run the test cases.
Fix typo in macro name (#500)

Remove macro registration hack (#499) In old versions of IntelliJ platform it was only possible to register
macros of custom names. The only way to provide custom macro was to
override one of the existing macros. We've been overriding
`FileRelativePath` macro.

Unfortunately, since version 201.x of IntelliJ platform the hack does
not work, because the data structure to keep the macros has been
changed from a HashMap to a List. This means, the entries are not
overriden, but appended to the end of the list. MacroManager looks up
only for the first ocurrence of the name, so the one in the end of the
list will never be found if the name is not unique. The change was
done in this commit https://github.com/JetBrains/intellij-community/commit/61838067fdd286140a51df64c9fcdbebc1543786

Luckily, the hack is not needed since
https://github.com/JetBrains/intellij-community/commit/fdf6dbcb8ccace8d9cad4f7e6400df834e197687.
This means, we can use any custom name for the macro

Fix pants version parsing (#490) ### Problem

Internally at Twitter, we append some extra information to the pants version number. However, this means that the pants version parser doesn't work when trying to parse stable releases (`1.20.0` as opposed to something like `1.20.0rc1`)

### Solution
Create a proper model for a `PantsVersion`, and use a validated regex to parse it.

Create additional inspection to allow to automatically add Python Facets to modules (#466) All BUILD files require a python interpreter and if a module doesn't contain one, there will be a warning shown unless the inspection is disabled. Now, we add an actionable quickfix that will automatically add a Python facet to a module in order to not replace a possible Java Jdk set already.

Overall quickfix algorithm:
1. If there is no python interpreter for the project, a window pops up where the user can choose the python interpreter to use. Otherwise skip.
2. If there is an already existing empty facet we remove it.
3. We add a new facet with either and existing interpreter or the one chosen in 1. step.

2. is needed since just adding an SDK is a flaky and I wasn't able to make it visible in the UI.

Call getAttachAnnotationsJarFix only once indexing is done (#480) Fixes #477

Don't retreive pants options in Event Dispatch Thread (#476) FileChangeTracker methods are always called in Event Dispatch Thread.
Pants Plugin implementation sometimes needs to retrieve pants options
in order to decide, whether to mark project as dirty. Unfortunatly,
Pants Options are retrieved via an external process call, what is
forbidden in the Event Dispatch Thread.

In this commit, the bahvior of the listener is changed in that way,
the pants options are retrieved before the listener is initialized,
on a thread from thread pool, and they're passed to listener's
constructor.

Unfortunately, pants options may be read only when a project
contains any modules. Therefore, it we can't just read them at
`projectOpened` stage, because the project may be initially empty.
That's why we register a ModuleListener in case when the project is
empty.

ORIGINAL MESSAGE

Before this commit, the list of the targets were stored in
`PantsProjectSettings::myTargetSpecs` field. Unfortunately, this list was based on the
contents of `myTargetSpecsBox` widget, which was cleared each time
when the "Pants->Settings" window was opened. As a result, the list
of targets was cleared each time during settings save.

The fix to this is just not to clean the list of targets in the
window.

But this led to a new issue. When the list of targets is presented
to the user, it's also possible for him to deselect target. During
save, the `myTargetSpecs` variable was based on the list of selected
targets, so after deselection and save, it was not possible to select
it again.

In order to overcome this, I put two lists to `PantsProjectSettings`
instead of `myTargetSpecs`:

 1. `allAvailableTargetSpecs` - used to build `myTargetSpecsBox` widget
 2. `selectedTargetSpecs` - to inform `pants` which targets it should
operate on

Contribute available build target types for completions inside of BUILD files (#473) This is a follow up for #455.
I rebased this branch on top of master and addressed the comment from the original PR so that full addresses are used instead of paths.

I replaced PantsBuildFileIndex which was only used for completions with PantsAddressesIndex, so now for all indexed BUILD files I take all of the target names from PsiFiles and add the default name also (equal to name of parent dir of BUILD file).

Initially I tried the suggested approach of reading all addresses from iml for all modules, but it made PantsCompletionTest#testAbsoluteAddress fail as it seems that project is not imported by this test properly.
Current approach gives wider set of target paths for completion (includes non-imported modules) and is more similar to the original behavior. Also it doesn't require project refresh to pickup new targets that were added.
If we'd rather prefer the smaller scope and relay on iml files, I can change the code, but I think I'd delete that single failing test as it would be quite an effort to fix it and it is also kind of covered by the new tests in this PR.

Add option to use IntelliJ compiler for Pants projects (#447) ### Problem
Often times shelling off to Pants has non trivial latency. This PR introduces using IntelliJ compiler for an imported Pants project to achieve faster turnaround time.

### Visible changes includes:
1. Add a checkbox at import time for IntelliJ Compiler
![Screen Shot 2019-12-12 at 10 28 38 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/596358/70738750-310b0a00-1cca-11ea-9f85-a2e067af93db.png)

Once selected, all the test configurations generated will invoke the default `Build` action as below
![Screen Shot 2019-12-05 at 9 29 06 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/596358/70258895-ede8ee00-1741-11ea-954b-f2613d302127.png)

instead of `PantsCompile`
![Screen Shot 2019-12-05 at 9 28 58 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/596358/70258902-efb2b180-1741-11ea-9fb1-aa43d86e1c39.png)

![Screen Shot 2019-12-05 at 9 40 08 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/596358/70259960-28ec2100-1744-11ea-8de3-fb25cea9e327.png)

3. Module content roots are further trimmed to the top level roots, so intellij won't double count the sources as it gathers all the sources for each content root.

In this case, `WelSpecXYZ` will be passed to the compiler twice, causing errors.

Exclude jars imported into the project for IntelliJ Junit/Scala runner (#331) ### Problem

Currently IntelliJ Junit/Scala runner will bring in all the jars imported into the project to classpath. This is not correct because not all jars imported are needed at runtime, thus causing classpath clashing issues sometimes, e.g. slf4j bindings.

### Solution

Exclude all jars in project except jars on the JDK path, IntelliJ installation paths, and plugin installation path

This patch also disables dynamic classpath for intellij runner since jars in project are excluded from the runner, the command should never be too long.

Currently all the pants command args from intellij pants plugin are hardcoded from the plugin, so we do not have a way to dynamically tweak per repo, which would be useful if when we want to inject flags for experimental pants features, debug flags, etc.

### Solution
Add a mechanism to recognize <build root>/.ij.import.rc file for dynamic argument changes per repo.

Add assertions for accidental bug fix from #312 (#320) In #312, a change was made to [`CompileAllTargetsInModuleAction.java`](https://github.com/pantsbuild/intellij-pants-plugin/pull/312/files#diff-41cc874d589fdbd635d9ca9f78149ef9) which stopped a bug that affected usage.

To reproduce the error, take a version of the plugin from any commit before b2a024a52a9287d74944400dc4f27a7a613989ba. Open a pants project A, then open a pants project B in a separate window. Click `Build->Compile Module '...'` with a source file from A open in the editor, which should work correctly. Switch to the window for project B, open a source file from B in the editor, then click `Build->Compile Module '...'`. The name of the module will be correct, but the `./pants compile ...` command will build the module from project A (which can be seen in the pants console -- the targets for project A are selected).

#312 accidentally fixed this (see link to diff at the top of this comment) by not mutating the private `module` field in `CompileAllTargetsInModuleAction`, but I didn't realize this modified any behavior until the bug above came to my attention. This adds multiple assertions to `OSSPantsCompileActionsTest#testCompileAllTargetsInModuleAction` to avoid a regression.

refactor pants invocation to only add cli options when appropriate (#318) The previous logic adds cli options (e.g. `--async`) to the command line if the version of pants supports e.g. `clean-all.async`, regardless of whether the command line contains the `clean-all` task. This makes it harder to construct different command lines with different tasks such as lint, because if `--async` is added without the `clean-all` task, pants throws an error. Instead, we ensure that cli options such as `--async` are only added if they are relevant to one of the tasks.

An alternative would be to make sure the cli options are less broadly scoped (e.g. `--clean-all-async` instead of `--async`), but adding a bunch of options that either go unused or interfere with the desired result sounds like it could cause problems later.

Throw exception on self cyclic dependencies (#288) ### Problem

Currently when there is a self cyclic dependency, the plugin will throw the following error which is very confusing.
```
Error:exception during working with external system: java.util.ConcurrentModificationException
        at java.util.TreeMap$PrivateEntryIterator.nextEntry(TreeMap.java:1211)
        at java.util.TreeMap$KeyIterator.next(TreeMap.java:1265)
        at com.twitter.intellij.pants.service.project.modifier.PantsCyclicDependenciesModifier.modify(PantsCyclicDependenciesModifier.java:32)
        at com.twitter.intellij.pants.service.project.PantsResolver.addInfoTo(PantsResolver.java:97)
```

### Solution
Despite there is still work to do on Pants side to enable cycle detection, we can at least check easiest case of self dependency, so the plugin will throw a more meaningful error instead of stacktrace.

### Result

Now it will give a presentable error during import `Error:Self cyclic dependency found <target name>`

Limit the scope of modules to obtain target addresses from before invoking Pants (#282) ## Problem
Currently the plugin will call configuration.getModules() in order to determine the target address associated with them, but `getModules()` behave differently in JUnitConfiguration and ScalaTestConfiguration:
* JUnitConfiguration returns a singleton list of module that the configuration belongs to
* ScalaTestConfiguration returns the transitive set of modules, causing 
1) More than one address getting invoked 
2) jar exclusion issues since not all its transitive modules are 1:1:1 conforming, which could introduce additional jars that meant to be excluded when invoking with just the single target.

## Solution
Make sure with Scala run configuration, we only get the module directly related to the test file instead of all its transitive modules.

## Result
As reflected in the test.

Move registering indexing listener to an earlier stage (#268) ## Problem
Only the indexing duration on the fly is captured, but not for the initial import.

## Solution
Move the listener registration to an earlier, i.e `initComponent` stage.

## Result
Manually tested that indexing data are logged at the initial import as well. There is currently no way to write such test, because the test framework does not mark indexing period, and there is already test covering artificially entering dumb mode at `com.twitter.intellij.pants.extension.PantsExternalMetricsListenerExtensionTest#testDurationIndexing`.

Fix JDK not set correctly from idea-plugin import (#267) ## Problem
If project is initiated from `idea-plugin` goal, project SDK is not set correctly because
* JDK creation is not registered in the core.
* The step to convert the seed Pants project to full bloom one does not explicitly set the project SDK.

## Solution
Explicitly set JDK if any on `idea-plugin` import.

Capture indexing duration on the fly (#265) ## Problem
There was no good way to capture indexing timing on the fly, but only on synthetic benchmark.

## Solution
This change uses `DumbService.DumbModeListener` interface to calculate the duration spent being dumb, i.e. the IDE is indexing.

## Result
In manual test, the results are captured; in unit test, the results are updated by artificially marking and unmarking dumb mode.

Add ability to cancel Pants process (#258) ## Problem
Once Pants process is invoked from IntelliJ, there is no easy way to cancel it equivalent to Ctrl + C on command line, and user has to manually find the process on command line.

## Solution
Keep track of active Pants process per project under `PantsMakeBeforeRun` and add GUI interface to trigger process termination.

Suggest refresh on project BUILD file changes (#254) ## Problem
BUILD file changes in the project does not notify user to refresh. The issue is more obvious after file changes out of band such as `git pull`.

## Solution

Remove unnecessary project wide file sync to reduce system load (#255) ## Problem

IDE may spend significant resources trying to synchronize everything in the project scope after every Pants invocation that may have changed the generated code. However, it is not necessary because interactively, changes only need to be reflected to user for the opened files, the rest of synchronization can be done at core's discretion.

## Solution
Remove project wide file sync.

Move Pants output to console view instead of notification channel (#242) ## Problem
Pants output used to go out via the IntelliJ notification channel with a few down sides:
1. No auto scrolling supported. If the message gets long, user has to manually scroll the message window.
2. Output does not show up exactly like the command line. E.g. compile error indicator `^` will show up off.
3. Cannot take advantage of IntelliJ hyperlink for user to click on the error to directly dump to what the error stems.

## Solution
Use a text console view, which has
1. Auto scroll by default
2. Correct output format
3. Capability to inject hyperlinks

Incremental project import for controlled indexing This change allows user to incrementally import a large project to minimize the time blocked by indexing before iterating on code or running tests.

Workflow:
1. At import stage, "Enable Incremental Project Import" option is added.
2. If selected, GUI will ask user how many levels of build graph to import given the max level. level 0 means target roots, level 1 means up to direct deps, so on and so forth.
3. If user wants to incrementally import more of the project, simply click 'Pants -> refresh project', then the dialog in step 2 will reappear once `pants export` is done.

Images:
level 0: shows `Distances` is not resolved.
level 1: shows `Distances` is resolved.

Sample stats for two internal projects regarding time saved before user can iterate:
Project 1: The indexing time is down from 590s to 346s (41% saving) with level 2 (total 8 levels)
Project 2: The indexing time is down from 350s to 160s (52% saving) with level 1 (total 6 levels)

Next step:
Currently IntelliJ does not recognize some of the test classes because their junit dependency is too far, so user has to trial and error to figure out the ideal depth to import, but we can optimize that down the road given

* Junit will be injected into `junit_test()` target
* Include all transitive `junit` dependees during import

Other minor changes:
* Pants cache invalidate action and Refresh project are now `DumbAware`, meaning they can be clicked while project is still indexing.

Fix 3rdparty dependency handling In the old way of handling 3rdparty jars (`->` means `depends on`):
If `source:a` -> `3rdparty:x` (with `x.jar`), we create `module(source:a)` and library `x.jar` then have `module(source:a)` depend on `x.jar`.

Problem:
If `3rdparty:x` is not simple jar, such as containing a jar as well as round trip dependencies back to source, say `source:a` -> `3rdparty:x` -> `source:b`, the plugin creates `x.jar` but cannot add `module(source:b)` to its dependency because intellij does not support so. Therefore the link `3rdparty:x` -> `source:b` is lost, causing resolution failures.

Fix:
For `3rdparty:x`, we create a empty module `module(3rdparty:x)` which depends on `x.jar` and `module(source:b)`, then create `module(source:a)` depending on `module(3rdparty:x)`. This way `module(source:a)` will still have transitive dependency into `module(source:b)`. Reference: https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/2016.2/content-root.html#d1659319e268

The essence of the change is straight forward and lies in `PantsLibrariesExtension.java` and `PantsCreateModulesExtension.java`. The test covering the changes is in `PantsResolverTest.java`.

The remaining changes are mostly test related due to the behavior change with module and 3rdparty dependency handling.

Other minor change:
1. Allow "show loaded files only" in project file tree view during indexing: `ProjectFilesViewPane.java`
2. Minor tweaks for metrics test.

Run ng-killall in tearDown to limit memory taken by ng processes `Abnormal build process termination` in https://github.com/pantsbuild/intellij-pants-plugin/issues/133

and eventually crashed later java process.

is to turn on ng only for compile, plus running ng-killall at the very beginning of
run (consists serveral subsequent pants test targets).

increasing the overall test time, but that hopefully we can address via

option, but would rather test more real settings for integration tests.

Fix threading assertion error when calling ProjectJdkTable.getInstance().addJdk Data structures in the IntelliJ Platform are covered by a single reader/writer
lock.  Writing data is only allowed from the UI thread, and write operations
always need to be wrapped in a write action with
`ApplicationManager.getApplication().runWriteAction()`. [1]

In this case, the following assertion error would happen if no jdk is defined.
```
Assertion failed: Write access is allowed inside write-action only (see com.intellij.openapi.application.Application.runWriteAction())
java.lang.Throwable
	at com.intellij.openapi.diagnostic.Logger.assertTrue(Logger.java:144)
	at com.intellij.openapi.application.impl.ApplicationImpl.assertWriteAccessAllowed(ApplicationImpl.java:1360)
	at com.intellij.openapi.projectRoots.impl.ProjectJdkTableImpl.addJdk(ProjectJdkTableImpl.java:199)
	at com.twitter.intellij.pants.service.project.wizard.PantsProjectImportBuilder.addIfNotExists(PantsProjectImportBuilder.java:86)
	at com.twitter.intellij.pants.service.project.wizard.PantsProjectImportBuilder.applyExtraSettings(PantsProjectImportBuilder.java:70)
	at com.intellij.openapi.externalSystem.service.project.wizard.AbstractExternalProjectImportBuilder.applyProjectSettings(AbstractExternalProjectImportBuilder.java:346)
```

[1] http://www.jetbrains.org/intellij/sdk/docs/basics/architectural_overview/general_threading_rules.html

Invoke pants regardless sources have changed because resources may have changed; pants options fix. Currently the changes in resources will not be detected by `hasDirtyTargets(holder)` in `PantsTargetBuilder` because it can only detect changes in `PantsBuildTargetType` whereas resources are handled by `ResourcesTargetType`. Therefore this RB disgard any check on `DirtyFilesHolder<PantsSourceRootDescriptor, PantsBuildTarget> holder`, so the behavior will be idential with `PantsCompile` in https://rbcommons.com/s/twitter/r/3607/

It is possible to design another Builder to handle the changes `ResourcesTargetType`, but it will also introduce the issue where both builders will be called without knowing whether the other has performed the job, so the work may be duplicated.

It is also possible to mark resources as sources, but UX will be bad because it will unnecessarily increase the load on already-slow source indexing, and many "syntax errors" will be found.

Obtain correct target for JUnit runs; Add JUnit and Scala plugin dependencies; Remove stale incremental integration test Earlier the external builder does not know which module is trying to run/test, so it simply compiles all modules in the project, which is inefficient. This change allows the affected module targets to be passed to the external builder.

Implementation:

PantsTargetBuilder will obtain target addresses to compile based on the affected modules (e.g. the module in junit run configuration, or a user right click on 'make module <module name>')

Issue (a): Since each compile contains a select few targets relating to the affected modules, and intellij thinks sucess of a compile  means the success for the whole project (at least I cannot find a way to specify compile success on module level yet), compile will not be triggered when no files are touched and user tries to compile/run a different module.

Workaournd: external builder will record the full target set for the last successful compile in <pants_workdir>/last_successful_plugin_run, and check it on the next run.

Minor issue (b): IntelliJ JUnit configuration has the granularity to a module. However a module may represent multiple targets (due to non 1:1:1 conforming BUILD files), so all its containing targets will be compiled.

Pick up jars with custom classifiers Earlier if a library is like this:

        "org.apache.hadoop:hadoop-common:2.7.1": {
            "default": "/Users/yic/.ivy2/pants/org.apache.hadoop/hadoop-common/jars/hadoop-common-2.7.1.jar",
            "sources": "/Users/yic/.ivy2/pants/org.apache.hadoop/hadoop-common/sources/hadoop-common-2.7.1-sources.jar",
            "tests": "/Users/yic/.ivy2/pants/org.apache.hadoop/hadoop-common/jars/hadoop-common-2.7.1-tests.jar",
            "javadoc": "/Users/yic/.ivy2/pants/org.apache.hadoop/hadoop-common/javadocs/hadoop-common-2.7.1-javadoc.jar"
        },

Only "default", "sources", and "javadoc" jars will be imported into the project, whereas the jar with custom classifier "tests" is ignored.

This change will import all jars with custom classifiers as binary jars.

From the code perspective:
1. LibraryInfo used to static fields default, sources, and javadoc, but custom classifiers can be anything and there can be any number of them. Now the class extends HashMap to handle the fields dynamically while maintaining the interface that LibraryInfo used to support.
2. A custom deserializer is introduced for LibraryInfo to parse the export output.

Using the correct Virtual File System refresh function before loading classpath The symptom is that, symlink /a/b/c/123 -> .pants.d/123 changes to /a/b/c/456 -> .pants.d/456, VFS still think /a/b/c/123 exists, resulting classpath not found in junit run. Ideally we want to refresh /a/b/c and recursively of its content.

According to http://grepcode.com/file/repository.grepcode.com/java/ext/com.jetbrains/intellij-idea/10.5/com/intellij/openapi/vfs/VirtualFileManager.java#VirtualFileManager.refreshWithoutFileWatcher%28boolean%29

Prevoisly used refreshAndFindFileByUrl "refreshes only the part of the file system needed for searching the file by the given URL and finds file by the given URL." This method will only non-recursively refresh, /a, /a/b/, to find /a/b/c.

Therefore, using refreshWithoutFileWatcher as it "Refreshes the cached information for all files in this file system from the physical file system", referenced to com.intellij.openapi.vfs.VirtualFileSystem#refresh

As far as I can obersve, the performance impact is minimal possilby because
1. only dist/export-classpath portion uses VFS and not the rest of the code imported in IJ
2. VFS refresh function may only invalidate the cache and then refreshes the content on demand.

fix escaping for no pex file, no pants executable error messages This changes messages with substitutions to make sure all single quotes are escaped by doubling them.

IntelliJ uses MessageFormat[1] when a bundled message contains `{`. `{0}` means insert the first argument here in MessageFormat's pattern language. Single quotes are used for escaping, so `'{0}'` is rendered as `{0}`. Double single quotes `''`, are escaped single quotes. Unpaired single quotes are discarded.

The thing this fixes is that `couldn't blah '{0}'` would render as `couldnt blah arg`. The intended string was `couldn't blah 'arg'`. What was happening was that the characters between the contraction's apostrophe and the first single quote of `'{0}'` were treated as a quoted string, and the last quote was discarded resulting in the unexpected message.

 1. http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/text/MessageFormat.html
